r 20%\nMohawk -j'\nNevada Consolidated 21%. 5\nNipiseing Mines 11 8\nNorth Butte 33%\nNorth Lake 8%\nOld Dominion 424*\nOsceola 1324*\nParrot (Silver and Cop.) 14%\nQuiney *80\nShannon 14\nSuperior 52% Superior\nand Boston Min 7*4\nSuperior and Pitta. Cop 15V?\nTamarack jf]\nP. S. Sm.. Kef. and Min 39%\nI*. S. Sm.. Kef. and Min., pfd 48%\nCtah Consolidated 25%\nCt ah Copper Co 50\nWinona \"It\nWolverine 1?0\nOffered.\nNEW YORK MINING STOCK.\nNEW YORK, November 5.\nMi'-e. offered 2.00\nCom stock Tunnel Stock, offered 20\nCouisiock Tunnel Bonds ID\nCon. Cat. and Va 1.00\nHorn Silver 35\nIron Rilrer 1.50\nLeadvllle Con., offered 10\nLittle Chief, offered 10\nMexican 1.10\nOntario 2.00\nOphlr 1.20\nStandard .45\nYellow Jacket 40\nNEW YORK BANKS.\nNEW YORK, November 5.-The report\nof clearing house banks for the week\nshows that the banks hold 14,886,000 more\nthan the requirements of the 25-per cent\nreserve rule. This is a decrease of *5.565,000\nIn the proportionate cash reserve\nas compared with last week. The statement\nfollows:\nDAILY AVERAGE.\nLoans 11.226.875.000 Inc. *832.000\nDeposits 1.187,876,000 Dec. 4,707.000\nCirculation 48.108,000 Ine. 3.000\nSpecie 235,398.000 Dee. 5.998.000\nLegal tenders 68.499.000 Dec, 744.000\nReserve 301.892,000 Dec. 6.742.000 j\nReserve required.. 296.994,000 Dec. 1.176,o00|\nSurplus 4.808.000 Dec. 5.565.000\nEx. U. S. deposits 5.307,000 Dec. 5.561,000 I\nACTUAL.\nLoans *1.220.800.000 Dec. *5.831,000\nlie posits 1,181..188.000 Dec. 10.930.000\nCirculation 48,214,000 Inc. 289,030\nSpecie 234.016,000 Dec. 4,865.000\nLegal tenders 66,210.000 Dec. 2,182.000\nReserve 301,125.000 Dec. 6.847.00O\nReserve required.. 295.396.000 Dec. 2,732.000\nSurplus 5.729.000 Dec. 3.815.000 1\nEx. U. 9. deposits. 0,138,000 Dec. 3,812,000 1\nNON-MEMBERS.\nLoans *1,134.688.000 Inc. *2.147,000\nSpecie 122.074,000 Dec. 1,080,000\nLegal tenders 21.731,000 Dec. 351.000 1\nTotal deposits 1,188,553 Dec. 2,311,000\nThe Financier will say:\nA loss in specie and legals amounting\nto *6.547.600. which a decrease of *10.- 1\n929,500 in deposits could not-overcome in\nthe matter of its effect on reserves,\nbroughtwthe surplus of the New York\nclearinghouse banks down *3,815,225. according\nto the statement of actual condit'ons\nfor the week ending Saturday, leaving\nthe margin of surplus above the 23\nper cent legal minimum at *5,728,2iK>,\nwhich is approximately the uame In\namount as that held one year ago.\nIt is worthy of note that following the\nfirst week in November last year surplus\nreserves of the New York banks began to\nrise, reaching *33.000,000 by the end of\nJanuary, 1910. Whether the same result\nwill be noted during the coming two\nmonths is conjectural.\nLoans last week showed a further de\ncune 01 dui tne total or loans\nis still nearly $40,000,000 above the deposit\nitem, a feature that tells its own\n*tory. The statement of averages issued 1\nSaturday shows about the same loss in\ncash reported by the tabulation of actual\nfigures, but the loan item increased $832.400.\n-whlla^deposits fell off $4,701,500, mak-\ning the surplus reserve $4,808,350.\nThe summary of the trust companies\nand other outside institutions in the statement\nfor the current week indicated un-\nimportant changes, loans having increased\n$-.000,000. Cash holdings fell off $1,431.-\n000. and there was a shrinkage of about\n$2,500,000 in deposits.\nTREASURY STATEMENT.\ni\nThe condition of the Treasury at the\nbeginning of business today was as\nfollows:\nTRUST FUNDS. Gold\ncoin $&00.83?.6C9\nSllrer dollars 4tr7.072.nia)\ni Sllrer dollars of ISWn S.MH.000\nI SUrer certificates outstanding 487,072,0\\W\nGUN KRAI. FUND.\nI fifandaril cilvor lur. in 1\nfund t2,570.(*vi\nCurrent liabilities U6.0ttl.70l\nWorking balance In Treasury offices. .TO.ttStt, l<0\nIn banks lo credit of treasurer of\nthe L'nlted States 35.4K?,jW7\nSubsidiary silver coin... ld-fiT' >1\nMinor oiin 8SC.12S)\nTotal bslauc*' In general fund.. 86,6t?7,339?\nme to a crop estimate 01 waw.ww Daies\nmblished by a Georgia authority, and as\nt had been rumored last Wednesday that\nhis report would be issued today, it was\nwtdently considered discounted in local\nircles. Moreover a crop estimate pubished\nby a prominent cotton firm in the\nlouthwest of ll,3t5o.t>00 bales and another\ny a local firm of ll,6i?,000 hales tended to\n>ITset the larger estimate mentioned\nihove. At any rate, right after the openng\nprices here firmed up and continued to\nidvance until the market had shown a net\nlain of 12a 17 points on active positions,\nvt this level there was considerable realizng\nand slight reactions occurred, but\nresh buying orders seemed to ream the\nnarket on every little di;.- and closing\nirices were not far off from the top.\nIt was considered from the action of\nhe market that big short interests were\ness willing to stand on their position\n?ver the week and the holiday Tuesday\nind the census report Wednesday mornng\nthan the bulls were to carry their\ncontracts, and possibly apprehensions of\ninfavoraoie weatner in the south foiiowng\nthe storms north of the belt had\niome influence on the day's trading. Other\nactors in favor of the advance were the\navorable showing of the week-end figures\nind the fact that southern spot markets\nis officially reported after the close of the\nnarket hYiday had shown advances of\nrom 1-16 to 3-16 of a cent, thus tending to\noniirni claims of a firmer spot situation\nus a result or rrost aamase reports. More\n>r less wire trouble was still reported tolay.\ndelaying southern news to no small\nxtent, but such few mtaaages as came\nhrough indicated firm spot holders and\ni somewhat better demand.\nNEW ORLEANS.\nNEW ORLEANS, La., November 5.?\nThe cotton market today continued to\nnan if est strength and the final prices\nvere 14 to 19 over the closing of the\nrevious day.\nThe opening in futures was at a dedine\nof 1 to 5 points on much lower\nables than due, but buying orders made\nheir appearance in volume immediately\ntfter the call, and at the end of the first\nlalf hour the decline was recovered and\ntrices put from 5 to 7 points over yesterlay's\nclose.\nThe market exhibited considerable\ntrength during the late morning, chiefly\ntn reports from some important sections\nif the belt that the crop .had been more\neriously damaged than was at first suptosed,\nand that even large and almost\nnature bolls had been killed and were\nurnlng soft and rotten. These accounts\ntarted a covering movement among\nhorts and the bulls quickly seized the\nid vantage to help hid the market up.\nkt the highest prices were 15 to 20\nloints over yesterday's close, and the\nlose was at a net advance of 14 to 19\njoints.\nSpot cotton firm, 1-18 up: middling,\n4%. Sales on the spot, 000 bales; to\n.rrive 1,400.\nFutures opened and closed stead?,\nhosing bids: November, 14.:t6: December,\n4.42; January, 14.50; March, 14.89; May,\n4.82; July 14.90.\nThe cotton market this week cloesd 38 to\n0 points higher than last week, the most\nictive months in the future market taken\nnto consideration. There was a gradual\nidvance from the opening, the lowest\n>rices being made on Monday, when the\nradlng months were 3 points up to 5\nK>lnts down compared with last week's\nlose. The high prices were made on\nJaturday, when the market stood 39 to 51\n>olnts over last week's last quotations.\nYom the lowest to the highest there was\n1 range of 4<1 to 50 points.\nA feature of the week was the tendency\no estimate the crop in a serious way.\nilany conservative firms always wait\nintl! after the first frost to put out their\nfuesses on the yield, and the freezing\nweather of last week was considered by\nhe majority to end the growth of the\n>lant.\nIn the early part of the week the bears\nried to offset any bullishness in the\nituation brought abou.t by the freeze\n>y estimates as high in some instances\nis 13.000,000 bales. These had their efect\nfor a short time, but from the midlie\nof the week more conservative estinates\nkept coming out, and their influence\non prices was marked. Belief in a\nnoderately small crop and accounts ot\ntreat damage to the crop by the cold\nvere the foundation of the week's ad,-ance.\nThe gist of the crop news of the week\nvas that the crop In every state of the\njelt had more or less been hurt by the\nccent cold weather. Ii\\ many localities\n:emperatures went to the freezing point\nind even below, and damage in these\nListricts was claimed by country cor espondents\nto have been more severe\nhan at first thought, as even large and\nilmost mature bolls were reported killed.\nIn the spot market prices advaqged\nbree-slxteenths, middling closing at 14%,\nigainst 14 3-16 last week and 14% this\nweek last year. Rales on the spot\n(.mounted to 2.905 hales, against 3,100\nast week and 3,005 this week last year.\nSales to arrive totaled 11,750 bales,\nigainst 6,230 last week and 4,450 this\nweek last year.\nFRUIT MARKET.\nNEW YORK, Noveber 5.?Evaporated\napples -move slowly, but prices are\nsteady; on the spot, fancy, is quoted at\n11%; choice, 8%a9%; prime, 7%all;\ncommon to fair, 6%a7%.\nPrunes are moderately active in a\njobbing way, and prices are steady,\nquotations range from 6 to 10c for\nCalifornias up to 30-40's, and 8a9% for\nv A on?_\nureguus, ?w-ov c.\nApricots are quiet but steady. Choice,\n12Hal3% extra choice, 13%al3?i;\nfancy, 13 s? al 4.\nPeaches are steady; choice, 7a7%; extra\nchoice, 8a8>6; fancy. 8^a9.\nRaisins show an easier undertone,\nowing to unsettled conditions on the\ncoast. Loose Muscatels are quoted at\n514a6^4: choice to fancy seeded, 6 >4 a\n7Vi: seedless, 5a6; London layers, 1.20a\n1.35.\nCATTLE MARKETS.\nNEW YORK.\nNEW YORK. November 5.?BeevesReceipts,\n1,070 head; feeling weak; dreesed\nt>eef slow and steady; exports, 817 head of\ncattle and 2,701 quarters of beef.\nCalves?Receipts, 312 head; feeling\nsteady; dress.d calves quiet but steady;\ncity drtwsed veals, 13 to 17; country\ndressed, to 15; dressed grassers and\nfed calves. 8H to 10.\nSheep and lambs?Receipts, 3,480 head;\nsheep dull and weak; lambs lower to Hell;\nmedium to fair sheep, 3.75 to 3.85; common\nto medium lambs. 5.00 to 0.00.\nHogs?Receipts, 1,074 head; nominally\nweak.\nCHICAGO.\nCHICAGO, November 5.?Cattle?Receipts,\n500 head; market weak; beeves.\n1.5oa7.65; Texas steers, 3.35a5.75; western\nsteers. 4.10a6.S5; stockers and feeders,\n-A. nnnro am/I hoiforo 9 ''\"aI? \"U\nI. JUaU.JU, VU*?D um? UVAft V*\ncalves. 7.50al0.25.\nHogs?Receipts. 8.000 head; market\nwreak, 3c to 10c lower for llslit; others\nsteady; light, 8.00a8.40; mixed, 7.75a8.33;\nlieavy, 7.40a8.30; rough, 7.40a7.63; good to\nchoice heavy. 7.65a 8.30; pigs, 7.70a?.40;\nbulk of sales. 7.73a8.40.\nSheep?Receipts. 2,000 head; market\nweak; native, 2.60a4.35; western, 2.63a\n1.30. Yearlings, 4.33a5.40: lambs, native,\n!.73a6.65; western, 4'.73a6.65.\nMETAL MARKETS.\nNEW YORK. November 3.?Metal\nmarkets were quiet and nominally unrhanred\nin the absence of exchanges. Tin.\n36.l7fea36.30; lake copper. 12.874ial3.13fe;\nelectrolytic, 12.87feai:}.00; casting, 12.5ua\n12.73; lead, 4.40a4.50; spelter, 5.80a5.90.\nid Trade.\nork; London.\nCOTTON MARKETS.\nNEW YOBK.\nNEW YORK, November 5.?'The cotton\nmarket showed continued strength today\n>n further covering and bull support with\n:he close firm at a net advance of 8al0\njoints.\nThe opening was steady at a decline of\nla5 points in response to somewhat disippointing\nLiverpool cables, but private\nidvices indicated that the relatively easy\nshowing of the English market had been\n1 _ A A. _ 4(1 AAA t_ 1\nLIST DIDNT SLUMP\nStrength of Market a Surprise\nEven to the Insiders.\nWAITS ON ELECTION DAY\nSpeculation Slows Down Fending\nCount of the Votes.\n\n\nELECTION BETS ON 'CHANGE\nMuch of Margin Buying of Past\nFew Weeks Has Been Merely\nPolitical Speculation.\n\nBY W. G. NICHOLAS.\nSpecial CorresDowlenco of The Star.\nNEW YORK. November 5. 1910.\nThis has been a very quiet and strong\nweek in the stock market. Anticipations of\nan election scare were not realized. The\ntendency was so pronounced in one direction,\nso far as the state of New York\nwas concerned, that there was no good\nchance to organize a raid that amounted\nto anything. At the same time there\nwas a sharp falling off in the volume of\nbusiness and a very general disposition\ntox sit tight on commitments already\nmade.\nThe election gambling spirit had been\npretty well gratified in bets previously\nmade on the stock market, and those who\nhad been figuring on the price effect of\nthe election next Tuesday did not care\nto go further. During the week preceding\nthere had been heavy profit taking\nand expectations were prevalent that quotations\nwould react sharply in consequence.\nThere was a market setback\nof several points, but the decline did not\ngo anywhere near as far as had been\ncommonly looked for. and even that\nsmall recession was made up in large\npart during the week under review.\nIndeed, in some cases new high records\non the movement were made, notably\nin Canadian Pacific, Amalgamated Copper,\nSmelters, United States Steel, Consolidated\nGas and quite a number of the\nspecialties. Steel got up to and past the\nprevious high point, and in the face of\nmost discouraging trade reports was well\nsustained throughout. Not less than\n130.(100 Shares bf the Inside long stock\nwere unloaded during tlie first three days\nof the week through two or three houses.\nThe stuff was taken without a tremor\nand at the headquarters of the organized\nbull party in that issue, expressions of\nsupreme confidence in a further advance\nafter the election are disseminated. This\nattitude is variously regarded. One\ntheory is that the bull syndicate has not\nsucceeded in unolading large lines bdught\non the way up, and that it is under the\nnecessity of making a higher market if\npossible, in order to get out with the\nprofits now shown on paper. Another\ntheory is that this bull contfngcnt is\ngenuinely in earnest and believes the\nstock to be worth a great deal more than\nit is now -selling for. Between these two\ntheories you pay your money and you\ntake your choice.\nBanks Control Speculation.\nThe banks played an important part\nin keeping speculation within bounds.\nAs pointed out in these letters, the\nbanking situation was not strong\nenough at any time to finance a campaign\nthat called for transactions anywhere\nnear 1,000,000 shares a day. It\ntook several strong hints for the bull\nleaders to get it througn their heads\nthat the banks were in earnest in ad*\nvising a drawing in of hornS, yet when\nthe truth was driven in hard enough'\nenthusiasm was subdued and the boom\nsubsided measurably. It was a knowledge\nthat this action would have to\ntaae place that induced the belief in\nan important reaction. The underlying\nstrength of sentiment proved, however,\nto be much greater than had been appraised,\nand we see the pleasant and\nsomewhat surprising fact of a substantial\nundertone extending beyond anticipated\nlimits of timeSpeculative\nattention is now being\nSi ven to the problem of \"what will\nhappen after the election.\" There is a\nwide divergence of opinion on this interesting\nissue. The surface idea is\nthat in the event of an overwhelming\nrebuke of Roosevelt in this state the\ngeneral public will enjoy a complete\nrestoration of confidence, which will be\nfollowed by a resumption of business\nactivity in every direction. It is upon\nthis theory that a large part of the investment\nbuying of the last three or\nfour weeks has been predicated. A fear\ngrows up, however, that no matter how\nimpressive the election in this part of\nthe country may be the voting in the\nwest and south will have a different\nslant, and results be open to_?. different\nconstruction. The thought obtrudes\ncontinually that no matter what happens\nthe country is very likely to have\ntwo Or three years of very sensational\npolitical agitation.\nFear Adverse Legislation.\nWith progressives and democrats in\ncontrol of one or both branches of Congress,\nas now seems to be entirely\nprobable, there can be no escape from\ndisturbing action along -several distinctive\nlines, tariff revision,' clamor\nfor more strongly defined regulation of\nrailroads and other corporations, prolongation\nof the fight over freight\nrates, all of this supplemented by a\nflood of investigations covering an infinite\nvariety of subjects ranging from\nthe Panama canal down to and including\nextravagance in governmental exurtl\n4 Soo 1 oont eil.nt iriit.. l.a.\njiciiiiiiui rn, (in ni voiiii iipuii'JIIS U)\nundesirable rich and every phase of the\nhigh and increasing cost of living.\nThat this line of agitation can proceed\nto the lengths that are threatened without\ndisturbing values and further checking\nthe return of prosperity cannot be\nhoped for.\nPeople who take this view of the\nfuture are not optimistic on the stock\nmarket. On the contrary, they believe\nthat the trend of prices will be downward\nfor two or three years, and that\nwe are in for that long a period of hard\ntimes, with all attendant embarrassments\nand privation.\nActual news developments this week\nhave not been of highest importance.\nThe publicity man of the steel trust\ncame out with another one of Ids famous\n\"canned\" interviews picturing*the condition\nof the iron trade as being luminously\nbright, although advices from the milling\ncenters are directly in contradiction of\nthese inspired expressions. A particularly\nimpressive part of tlds interview\nwas the announcement that the steel\ntrust management was engaged in the\nmanufacturing business, and was paying\nno attention to market manipulation or\nthe fluctuations in the prices of stocks.\nMade Wall Street Laugh.\nThis sort of thing may be swallowed\nby an innocent public, but it certainly\nraised a laugh in Wall street, where\neverybody knows tlat the steel trust\nmanagement includes several of the most\nactive market plungers in America, men\nwho ai'e notorious as being desperate\ngamblers and who specialize on steel.\nHowever, If that sort of output is the\ntonic required, the premier publicity\nagent of the corporation is equal to any\ndemand that may be imposed upon him\nin this respect. He is certainly a star\nperformer in handing out the dope. As\na mixer of good medicine lie has no\nequal. The trouble is fewer people take\nit than formerly. It has begun to pall\non the taste.\nSpeaking of the steel trust, it is expected\nthat the statement of tonnage on\nthe books, due in two or three days.\nwill be very discouraging, and the public\nmind has been prepared for the bad\nshowing. 1\nEverybody is glad the political campaign\nIs drawing to a close. There is\nnot much chance for traders to get a\ncomprehensive line on the market until\nafter the ballots are counted and a little\ntime given to estimate effects and consequences.\nThe price changes of late are\nlittle more than ?a reflection of the betting\nodds on the election of Mr. Dl* to be\nGovernor of New York. As the odds\nt\nstrengthened, prices advance and the\nebbs and flows in the odds formed a basis\nfor operations on the stock exchange.\nFor the moment other considerations had\nto take a back seat. Later on the tundamentals\nwill get back into tne forefront.\nAs some one pertinently remarked,\nthere is more virtue in a $9,090,000,000\ncrop than in the success of any political\nparty or the defeat of any of the new isms\nwhich may be advanced by the apostles\nof so-called progressive creeds and deviations\nfrom the straight line of sane\nand sober procedure.\nRailroad Earnings Disappoint.\nRailway earnings are not coming in\nas owners would like to see. Comparisons\nwith the splendid records of\nlast year are unfavorable. Last year's\ngross was a record-breaker, and\nalthough there was a tremendous increase\nin operating expenses, net results\nheld up remarkably well. The returns\nthat are coming in now show a\ndecrease in gross, and also a falling\noff fn cost of carrying on the business.\nRailroads are practicing economies in\nmany directions, although it would appear\nthat they are spending a lot of\nmoney in maintenance and thjit sort\nof thing, which might also oe savea\nwithout serious detriment (o the plant.\nThis is giving shippers a good peg to\nhang the charge and argument that\nthe railroads are spending money in\norder to influence the interstate commerce\ncommission in tlie great tight for\nand against an advance in freight rates.\nThere is just enough to this charge\nto make it effective. The inference\nfrom this condition of affairs is that\nthe railroads are giving themselves a\nshade the best of it in the matter of\nbookkeeping, and that the transportation\ncompanies are in reality in better\nshape than they try to make it appear.\n\nThe activity and strength in Amalgamated\nCopper and Smelters was largely\nthe result of manipulation. Smelters lias\nbeen able to put through a piece of\nfinancing based on its ability to borrow\n$15,000,000 to pay off back debts and to\nadd to its working capital. Knemjes of\nthe Smelting company are cruel enough\nto say that a part of the money thus borrowed\nwill in some indirect way make\ngood the payment of dividends, an allegation\nwhich is being violently denied\nfrom headquarters. The background of\nthe copper share strength is a supposed\nimprovement in the copper metal situa|\ntion. This improvement is one point real\nand about five points artificial. The manipulation\nis. well handled and tips that\nhave gone out are being made good.\nEventually the program will probably\nland the public with a mass of copper\nand smelter stocks at high prices.\nNovember disbursements of all sorts\nfor corporation dividends and interest\nwill approximate $120,000,000, instead of\naround $110,000,000, as the statisticians\nfirst figured.\nNEW YORK PRODUCE.\nNEW YORK, November 5.?Flour?Dull\nand barely steady Sprinig patents, 5.15a\n5.40: winter straights, 4.10a4.25; winter\npatents, 4.40a4.75; spring clears, 4.15a4.40;\nwinter extras No. 1, 3.40a3.70; winter extras\nNo. 2. fi.25a3.40; Kansas straights,\n4.00a4.75. Receipts, 21,352 barrels; ship,\nments, 18,224 barrels.\nTtve flour?Steady; fair to food. 4.00a\n4.25; choice to fancy. 4.25a4.40.\nBuckwheat flour?Quiet; 2.10 per 100\npounds.\nBuckwheat?Quiet; American, 00 c. I. f.\nNew York; Canada, 55 c. I. f. New York\nfor export.\nCorn meal?Steady; fine white and yellow,\n1.15al.20; coarse, l.10al.l5; kiln dried.\n3.0O.\nRye?Steady; No. 2 western, 84% f. o. b.\nNew York\nBarley?Firm; malting;, 76aS2 c. I. f. Buffalo.\nWheat?Spot firm; No. 2 red, 95% elevator\nand 95% f. o. b. afloat; N?. 1 northern\nDuluth, 1.12% f. o. b. afloat. Futures\nmarket was quiet but very steady on firm\ni cables, small world's exports and eom[\nplajpts of Hessian fly and lack of moisture\nin some sections of the winter wheat\nbelt, closing %a% net higher. December\n95%a96, closed 96%; May. 1 0214a 1.0$%,\nclosed 1.02%; July closed 1.01%. Receipts,\n134,000 bushels; shipments. 11,000 bushels.\nCorn?Spbt barely steady; No. 2 corn,\n57% elevator, domestic basis to arrive c.\ni. f. and 58c 1. o. b. afloat. Futures market\nwas without transactions, closing net\nunchanged. December closed 55%; May\nclosed 50%. Receipts, 38,350 bushels;\nshipments, 558 busht's\nOats?Spot steady; standard white, 37%;\nNo. 2. 88%; No. 3. 37%; No.- 4. 37%.\nFutures market was without transactions,\nclosing at to net advance. November\nclosed 37%; December, 2i7%; May,\n40; July. 30%. Receipts, 28,975 bushels;\nshipments, 720 bushels.\nHay?Quiet; prime, 1.10a1.12%; No. 1,\nI.h7%al.l0; No. 2, 95al.00; No. 3. 80a90.\nHops?Steady; state, common to choice\n1910, 18a23; 1909. 15al8; Pacific coast, 1910,\n14al8; 1909, 10al4.\nHides?Quiet; Central America, 21%;\nBogota, 22a23.\nleather?Steady; hemlock firsts, 23%a\n25%; seconds, 21%a23; thirds, 19a20; rejects.\n10al7.\nPork?Dull: mesg. 20.00; family, 24.00a\n25.00; short clear, 21.00a22.50.\nBeef?Steady; mess, 15.00al5.50; family,\n19.Wa20.00; beef hams, 23.00a25.09.\nCut meats?Steady; pickled bellies. 10\nto 14 pounds. 15al8; pickled hams, 14%.\nBard?Steady; middle west prime, 11.80a\nII.90; refined steady; continent. 12.50;\nSouth America. 13.25; compound, 9%a9%.\nTallow?Firm; prime city hogsheads,\n7%; country. 7%aS%.\nCottonseed oil?Steady; prime crude\nsoutheast, fi.20a0.27; prime summer yellow.\n7.49a7.53; November, 7 40a7.42; December.\n7.4?a7.42: January, 7.45a7.4fi; February.\n7.48a7.50; March. 7.53a7.54.\nWool?Quiet; \"domestic fleece, .'to.\nPetroleum?Steady; refined. New York,\nbarrels. 7.40; refined New York, bulk, 8.90;\nPhiladelphia, barrels, 7.40; Philadelphia,\nbulk. 3.90.\nRosin?Quiet; strained common to good,\n6.20.\nTumentlne?Steady; machine, barrels.\nso.\nRfce?Quiet; domestic, 2>4a5U; patna,\n5'-sa6.\nMolasses?Quiet; New Orleans kettle,\n32*42.\nRaw sugar?Steady: Muscovado. SO test,\n3..'Mi; centrifugal, 06 test. 3.86; molasses\nsugar. 80 test. 3.11. Refined sugar, quiet.\nCut loaf. 5.4<?; crushed. 5.3<i; mold A,\n4.05; cubes. 4.85; XX powdered, 4.35:\npowdered, 4.70; granulated, 4.?>o; diamond\nA, 4.60: confectioners' A. 4.4<>; No. 1,\n4.35; No. 2. 4.30; No. 5, 4.25; No.\" 4. 4.20;\nNo. 5. 4.15; No. 6. 4.10; No. 7. 4.05; No.\ns. 4.00: No. O, 3.05; No. 10, 3.00; No. 11,\n3.85; No. 12, 3.80; No. 13, 3.75; No. 14,\n3.75.\nPotatoes, cabbages, peanuts and\nfreights quiet and unchanged.\nCHICAGO GRAIN.\nCHICAGO. November 5.?Important\npurchases by the influential interests that\nhave been on the buying side most of the\nweek forced wheat higher today. The\nclose was at a net advance of t?a%c to\n\"ialc. It was generally believed tonight\nthat the greater part of the local short\nlines, big and little, had been covered.\nCorn at the finish showed a decline of Ua\n%c to a shade higher, and provisions were\nthe same as last night to an additional\ncost of 37^c.\nSome new buying of wheat today was\nbased on the idea that a good rally was\ndue after such a long continued decline.\nAnother bullish influence was an advance\nin prices at Paris attributed to storm\ndamage reports from southwestern\nEurope. The fact was noted also that\nworld shipments promised a decrease.\nMoreover, receipts at primary points during\nthe week had lessened about 4,<WU,U0J\nbushels from the figures at the corresponding\ntime last year, whereas shipments\nout of the same cities were short\nbut little more than 2,000,000 bushels.\nBetter call developed here for cash\njvheut, and there were reports of further\nshipping sales at Winnipeg, presumably\nlow grades to Germany. Selling pressure\nwas off the entire day, the market advancing\nsteadily f-om the start, except for a\nbrief dip early. The close left prices\nwithin 'fee of the top for the session?a\ntwo-day bulge. December ranged from\n8s% to 85>?fe, with last sal^p ??alc up at\nW)Via8y%.\nCorn support was as good as expected,\nthe wet map having been discounted. May\nfluctuated between 40 and 416^, closing\nnet lower at 49a49'i. Cash demand\nwas limited. Latest figures for No. 2 yel'\n\nlow was JUTtdtM.\nOats hardened a little because primary\nreceipts for the week were only 3.000,000\nbushels against 4,434,000 bushels a year\nago. The market, however, was dull. May\nsold from 34s* to ^>4% and finished the\nsame as yesterday, 341?.\nThere was a strong turn in all hog\nproducts, owing to a short run of hogs.\nAt the wind-up pork was unchanged to\n37%e higher, lard no different from last\nnight to 5a7Vi dearer, and ribs at an advance\nof 5a7%c to 10c.\nFUAJCIAL.\nSafe Deposit Boxes for\nRent, $3.00 a year up.\nISevei\nMxfl. <?_ IU\nI/in a n\nB. F. Sau\nJames F.\nAlex. S. C\nHoward 3\nEdward I\nWilliam H.\nAlex. Clarke\nAnthony Ga\nJohn B. Gei\nWm. Hahn,\nElectric Light Bills can be\npaid at any of our Banks.\n39\nCom\nWEEK'S RANC\nCorrected to the Close of\nthe New York\nRailway and His\nThe following table shows the wee]\nIndi