 ago.\nTwelve Couples' Golden Weddings.\nFrom the London Standard.\nA dozen couples have celebrated their\ngolden weddings at Morbeeque. a Belgian\ntown of 3.000 inhabitants. The twelve\nfamilies were serenaded in turn by a\nband outside their windows according\nto their years of married life.\nTlio nMouf <.i>nnlo ta M and Mme. Del\nbuilt, who have been married fifty-six\nyeA-s. and they headed the procession of\nvenerable happy lovers to church. A\nbanquet was g'ven to the twelve families\nby the municipal councilors. In the\nafternoon presents were brought to them\nby almost every man, woman and child\nin the town.\nt\nranurom.\nrrcasury.\nDrafts issued on all\nForeign Countries.\nNK,\nN.W.\nSt. s.w. I\nPresident\nPresident I\n>8\nSecretary g\nTreasurer\nTreasurer i\ni H. Ruppert, g\nSaul,\ncs F. Shea,\ni Shughruc, jg\nTravelers' Checks and\nLetters of Credit issued.\nPaid\nts. B\n:ited,\nCities Service Co.\n(Henry L. Doherty, President)\nI Preferred Stock..Yielding\ni Common Stock. .Yielding 5j6\nPublic Subscription dosos Nov. 10, tflf\nParticular attention givra the small\nInvestor.\nWrite\nWilliams, McDonnell Coleman\nBonds Stocks\nno WALL ST. Phone SS21 John RBW YORK\nZJ.sn LUA.OS Ui.SiillOt Ut>\nPROPERTY.\nLowest prevailing rates. Quick eerrtcs.\nModerate charges.\nHeiskefil McLeran,\noc1S-7d 1403 H ST. K.W.\nUnder Gov. Supervision.\nI German-American\nBuilding j\nAssociation\n\nw X\n300 B Street S. E.\n4 i\nz\ni We pay 6 per cent to\nI our members. I\nv we-tf,tf\n0 0001\nTHE EIGHTEENTH ANNUAL MEETING OF\nthe Mutual Serial Building ^Association will\ntake place on Monday, November 7. at 7:80\np.m., In St. Dominic's Hall, flth and F sts.\ns.w. Tim first payment In the nineteenth\nseries will be due. Shares, one dollar per\nmonth. $1,000 loaned on five shares for a payment\nof ten dollars per month. An amendment\nto the constitution to pay fi per cent\nInterest will be considered. Persona wbo cannot\nattend the meeting may pay the treasurer.\nK. Harrison Joimsju, at fala office, 306 7th\nst. a.w. J. 80NDHEIMER.\nJ. J. DERMODY. President.\nSecretary. ocao fit\nFOREIGN MARKETS.\nLONDON, November 5.?The stock market\nduring the week was more active anil\ncheerful, especially the investment section.\nand closed generally higher, with a\nhardening tendency. The prospects of an\nimprovement in the bank reserve and the\nbelief that the monetary stringency Is\nonly temporary brought fresh demands\nfor investment issues. Consols led the\nBritish shares with an advance of a half,\nthe reinvestment of dividends helping the\nbetterment. The French ministerial crisis\nchecked operations in foreign honds,\nwhile the Paris settlement brought about\nliquidation in mining shares. But more\nconfidence in buying at the week end\nput values on a firmer basis. Rubber\nshares were benefited by reports that\nAmerica was buying the raw material\nfor forward delivery.\nAmerican securities were fairly activa,\nbut irregular. Dear money and poor\n1 ?*1.. \\l'o 1\nIr urn 1111 v rai 11111^3 pai n,v cucvaou\nstreet pools buying. whtch was prominent\nin United StateR Steel. Union Pacific ami\nJ opper shares. The inarket today was dull\nand uncertain, pending the result of the\nelections in the Unit ad States, and the\nclosing was from two points higher to\none lower than last Saturday.\nThe Bank of England, in keeping tight\ncontrol of the money market in order to\nmake its per cent rate effective. caused\na sharp rise in discount rates, hut the\ngeneral opinion is that the stringency\nwill relax in the near future.\nMoney was scarce and dear today. DisI\ncount rates were Arm.\nThe stock market was moderately acI\ntive, with a cheerful tone. Gilt-edged\n1 securities were supported by investors\n1 and Kaffirs by Paris. Shell transport\ni and oil shares were strong on rumors of\nI an agreement with the Standard Oil Com'\n1 pany. Home rails were affected by itI\nports of labor trouble.\nAmerican securities were quietly suj>i\nported at a fraction over parity, but business\nwas restricted pending the elections\ni in the United States.\nPARIS. November i?Prices were generally\nfirm on the bourse today. Spanish\nsecurities were affected by the Catalonian\ntroubles.\nBERLIN, November fi.? Prices were\nsomewhat lower on the bourse today.\nDRY GOODS MARKET. 1\nNEW YORK. November .\"..-The dry\ngoods markets were quiet and steady for\nthe day. Linens and burlaps are strong\nwith prices tending higher. A good advance\nbusiness is being done by jobbers\non fine and fancy cottons.\nThe Outcome.\nFrom Llnoincott's.\nScratch a principle, and you will flat\nprejudice.","height":"37888","width":"30744"}}
